Cracking Passwords on Linux Systems:

Top 1000000 passwords: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/danielmiessler/SecLists/master/Passwords/Common-Credentials/10-million-password-list-top-1000000.txt

4GB password dictionary: 64 million passwords: https://crackstation.net/crackstation-wordlist-password-cracking-dictionary.htm 

rockyou dictionary: https://github.com/brannondorsey/naive-hashcat/releases/download/data/rockyou.txt

CrackStation.  For MD5 and SHA1 hashes, there is a 190GB, 15-billion-entry lookup table, and for other hashes, they offer a 19GB 1.5-billion-entry lookup table.

- /etc/passwd is a text file that contains the attributes of (i.e., basic information about) each user or account on a computer running Linux or another Unix-like operating system. http://www.linfo.org/etc_passwd.html

- /etc/shadow file stores actual password in encrypted format (more like the hash of the password) for user’s account with additional properties related to user password.  https://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/understanding-etcshadow-file/

- tail –n -4 /etc/shadow: displays last 4 lines (tail) of the file shadow

- John the Ripper is a fast password cracker, currently available for many flavors of Unix, macOS, Windows, DOS, BeOS, and OpenVMS. https://www.openwall.com/john/    https://tools.kali.org/password-attacks/john

- Hashcat - Hashcat is the self-proclaimed world's fastest password recovery tool. It had a proprietary code base until 2015, but is now released as open source software. https://hashcat.net/hashcat/

- ProFTPD is an FTP server. ProFTPD is Free and open-source software, compatible with Unix-like systems and Microsoft Windows. Along with vsftpd and Pure-FTPd, ProFTPD is among the most popular FTP servers in Unix-like environments today. http://www.proftpd.org/ 

- running the command "proftpd" starts the ftp server.

- johnny is the GUI for John the Ripper https://openwall.info/wiki/john/johnny


//To Do Next
1. Download either of the password dictionaries presented earlier in this document, or another of your choice.
2. Download and install hashcat and/or johnny on your computer (VM). 
3. Using your choice (compatible) of hashing scheme generate a test shadow file with a few password hashes. Be certain that the password is present in the dictionary you have downloaded.
4. Employ hashcat or johnny to crack the password by providing the dictionary and shadow file. Measure time it takes to break it.
5. Record a screen capture video to demonstrate your understanding and working of the above steps (not more than 3 mins long). You can use https://screencast-o-matic.com/screen-recorder for screen recording.
6. Submit this video on the blackboard.

